sentences: George Washington (born October 18, 1907) was an American jazz trombonist.
He relocated to Philadelphia in 1925 and played with J.W. Pepper before moving to New York City shortly thereafter.
In 1931, he began playing with Don Redman, and gigged with Benny Carter in 1932 and Spike Hughes in 1933.

From 1937 to 1943, he played in Louis Armstrong's orchestra.
From 1947 he led his own ensemble, playing in California and the Las Vegas Strip.
He and drummer Johnny Otis collaborated often, and in 1960 Washington worked with Joe Darensbourg.

While not a path-breaking major figure, Washington was a consistently inventive soloist whose fine work can be heard not only with the Blue Rhythm Band but with Armstrong's late 1930s' band and Count Basie.
In New York, Washington studied under Walter Damrosch at the New York Conservatory, playing with various ensembles in the late 1920s.
He began playing trombone at age ten, and attended Edward Waters College in the early 1920s.
The range of his talent can be assessed on, for example, Kokey Joe (hot and growly, rangey) or Harlem After Midnight.
